Project Report

Team name

Author

Lila Weiner, Gabrielle Bliss, Kenneth Yeon, and Riley Otsuki

Published

December 5, 2022

Abstract
An analysis of the representativeness and ethical distribution of various museumsâ art collections will primarily advise museum acquisition teams of where their collections lack in terms of diversity. Our team chose to analyze the distributions of artwork and artists represented in the Tate, MoMA, and Block museum collections through variables such as artwork medium, artwork size, artwork age, artist nationality, and artist distribution. Additionally, we provide intervals of creation dates corresponding to different artwork variables, such as medium, in order to provide acquisition teams at museums with a medium to look into acquiring if they are looking for an artwork of a specific creation date.

1 Background / Motivation

Museums are a primary mode of connecting people with artâthey are integral to our perceptions of art, the people who create it, and our subconscious conclusions regarding what art is deemed important versus what art is not. In more recent times, the practice of ethically cataloging artist and artwork data has become a more prominent topic of discussion in museums internationally. Museums are growing aware of âreevaluat[ing] their practices in order to foster inclusionâ [1]. Many museums express their commitment to ethically representing marginalized groups as the vast majority of the historical art canon has been largely formed through a westernized lens. Our team was interested in the demographic of artists and dates of creation for works in major Euro-centrically focused museums, and the patterns that emerge. Additionally, because the nature of data analysis is to distill artwork to its raw descriptive characteristics (artist, materials, date of creation, etc.), this kind of exploration inspired our team to look at art in a way that goes beyond the visual norm. We were interested to see how we can gain a new understanding of art and museums through data-driven research, while also making interesting discoveries that could inform recommendations to museum curators and other interested parties.

2 Problem statement

The four analysis questions our group chose to focus on are outlined below. These questions delve into four different areas that help paint a comprehensive picture of the demographics and diversity of artwork and artists characteristics, while also illuminating and potholes in the data cataloging of certain museums

  1. When are artworks with unknown creation dates most likely created based on other artwork characteristics?

  2. What materials and dimensions are most popular in each museumâs collection? Why might these differ/prove to be similar? Have certain materials become more popular as we have progressed into the twenty-first century?

  3. How old are the artworks in the collections of each museum? How many years after creation are artworks acquired by museums?

  4. What is the demographic of the artists represented through the MoMA and Tate Museumâs collections? Are there trends nationality or gender overall? How does this data compare to the demographic of artists at a smaller, university museum like the Block?

3 Data sources

To conduct our analysis, we utilized multiple open-access datasets, released to the public by the MoMA and Tate museums. More specifically, the MoMA artwork dataset contains 140,848 entries, which represent the entirety of the art pieces âthat have been accessioned into MoMAâs collection and cataloged in [their] databaseâ [2]. The MoMA data for artwork includes the date of acquisition. The MoMA artists dataset specifically contains 15,243 entries, each unique, and represents all the artists who are featured in MoMAâs collection through their artworks and have been cataloged in the MoMA database. The specific, pertinent variables present in this dataset for MoMA are, the artistsâ names, nationalities, genders, birth years, and death years. The Tate artwork dataset contains information for the some 70,000 artworks that Tate owns. This open-access datasource was last updated in 2014. The artists dataset for Tate has information such as name, gender, yearOfBirth, yearOfDeath, placeOfBirth, and placeOfDeath for about 3,500 associated artists. Missing data is present in these four datasets and both museums deem these entries as ânot curatoriallyâ approved. However, we feel as though the data provided in the open-access files provides enough information to perform analysis of the demographics of artists and artworks represented in these collections. Finally, to supplement the above datasets, our group created datasets for the collection of artwork/artists at the Block Museum of Art on Northwestern campus. To create csv files for these two areas of interest, we created a full DataFrame for all artwork information and a full DataFrame for all artist information found in the Blockâs website. This data was held in multiple pages of data tables, which we imported and concatenated together to create comprehensive DataFrames that were then translated into csv files. Unfortunately, the Block data lacked a lot of the variables present in the MoMA and Tate datasets, so this data could only be used for comparison in certain analysis topics, such as gender and nationality distribution of artists represented in the museums.

The links to our data sources are in references ,Tabular data for artists is in appendix.

4 Stakeholders

The pertinent stakeholders to our analysis of the equal representation and ethical cataloging of major international art museums are individually elaborated on below.

Museum acquisition teams, as well as curators and collectors will be interested in the patterns/trends in our analysis that display distributions that deviate from their goals and pledges. As those responsible for representing art on a prestigious platform like that of MoMA and Tate, understanding where their collection falls short may help them know where to increase funding or focus their acquisitions.

Museum attendees are concerned with viewing an art museum with a vast selection of art exhibitions with beautiful artworks of different cultures and stories. Museums have a responsibility to present artworks that are representative of different cultures/historical facets. An artwork collection that is not varied is limiting public perception of art.

Art history or museum researchers and similar people in academia may be limited due to the fact that Tate and MoMA do not possess a representative collection of different historical art canons or art created by underrepresented groups. They may find our data analysis to be useful in regards to providing a guide to museums on where to focus acquisitions in order to be more ethical and representative in their collections. Museum researchers also might find trends regarding mediums in relation to time reveal new things about the history of artwork in museums.

5 Data quality check / cleaning / preparation

The first step in using the artwork datasets was to prepare the columns which signified creation date. We wanted the creation dates to be numeric objects, rather than strings. These strings were inconsistent in format (i.e.Â âDesigned 1912, drawn 1914â and âca. 1946-47â). To extract the creation date, we first changed all of the NaN values in the column from floats to strings. Next, we found the year values occurring in the strings using findall() under the âreâ library. We then had a list of lists containing the years as strings. From here, each list of strings was passed through a series of if statements. If there was only one, four digit string in the list, that string would serve as the creation date. If there were two four digit strings that were less than 10 years apart, the average of these numbers would serve as the creation date. The output was a list of lists, most of which contained one, four digit string. There were still some unique dates that required individual manipulation, and thus these values were not included in the following analysis.

        list_of_values[i] = 'x'

block_works['Date'] = list_of_values

c = []
for i in range(6074):
    c.append(re.findall('\d+', list_of_values[i] ))

#if there is only one four digit number, we want to use that number. 
for i in range(6074):
    if len(c[i])>0:
        for j in c[i]:
            if len(j)<4:
                c[i].remove(j)

#if there are more than two numbers detected, we will not be including the artwork in analysis

            c[i] = [(int(c[i][0]) + int(c[i][1]))/2]
    elif len(c[i])>3:
        c[i] = []

good_indexes = []
for i in range(6074):
    if len(c[i])==1:
        good_indexes.append(i)
        c[i]=int(c[i][0])
block_works['Date'] = c

block_works_cleaned['Date'] = pd.to_numeric(block_works_cleaned['Date'])

For the artist datasets for each museum, the pertinent columns on gender and nationality needed to be cleaned before using for analysis and visualizations. The Block museum failed to possess data for artist gender, so only the Tate and MoMA datasets were analyzed in this respect. For the Gender column in both artistsâ datasets, the counts of each value were visualized in a series to primarily determine if any of the values in the column needed to be cleaned. The Tate dataset only included two values for the Gender column, âMaleâ and âFemaleâ. Therefore, this column was left alone. In the MoMA dataset however, the values in the gender column took on multiple values that needed to be combined to create clean data. The values in the MoMA gender column were âMaleâ, âFemaleâ, âmaleâ, âNon-Binaryâ, âfemaleâ, and âNon-binaryâ. These values were cleaned with an applied lambda function that consolidated the similar value names together to create three categories: âMaleâ, âFemaleâ, and âNon-Binaryâ.

The missing values in the Tate artist dataset made up less than 4% of the dataset, so the assumption was made that the overall distributions would not be affected by ignoring these values. Even though the MoMA dataset has a significantly larger amount of missing values, we felt as though the assumption still held in regards to gender distribution. Additionally, taking into account the ethical cataloging notion held by many major museums, we assumed that if a gender was missing, then an artist either did not want their gender specified, or the museum did not want to assume a gender of the artist based off of, say, the artistâs name.

For the nationalities of the artists, major cleaning was required for the Block and Tate museum datasets as they did not have a singular nationality column. MoMA did not need to be majorly cleaned as it already possessed a specific nationality column. For the Block Museum artist dataset, the nationality could be observed as a part of the string in the date column. If the date column was completely empty for an entry, we dropped the row. For the remaining entries, the Date column had to be split where commas were present into multiple columns that we extracted in a new dataframe. We assumed that the nationality would be in its own section based on comma splicing, most likely in the first spliced column judging based on the general format of the Date column in this Block artists dataset. If there was no value in the second column of the separate columns representing the split Date column, the nationality was the value assumed to be in the first column. Then, if the string âfoundedâ, or â-â (representing the dash between dates, which was also present in the date column) was found in the first column being cleaned to ideally only contain the artist nationalities, these values were dropped. Finally, a couple similar values for nationality were combined into the same value for ease in distribution. For example, âAmerican installation artistâ was cleaned to be included in the âAmericanâ nationality group.

For the Tate artists, there was also no nationality column explicitly present. To display this distribution, the birthplace of the artist was assumed to be analogous with their nationality, as the country in which one is born is a country the person has citizenship in. Thus, the âplaceOfBirthâ column in the Tate dataset was cleaned to adequately display the distribution of the main nationalities represented by the artists present in this museumâs collection. For example, artists with âDeuschlandâ or âGermanyâ mentioned in the string under the âplaceOfBirthâ column were cleaned to be grouped in the âGermanâ nationality. This process was applied using an applied lambda function which completed analogous processes the German example but for many countries. Entries that had no value in the variable âplaceOfBirthâ were dropped, which was less than 15% of the data. We assumed that this would not drastically skew the distribution of nationality greatly. While we could have imputed nationality for these missing values based on the âplaceOfDeathâ variable, we were wary to do so based on the fact that artists could have moved countries, and their location/country of death would not necessarily reflect accurately on nationality. Thus, the distribution is based primarily off of artists whose places of Birth were present in the dataset.

6 Exploratory Data Analysis

6.1 Analysis 1

By Kenneth Yeon

Determining an estimation of when an artwork with an unknown date was created requires us to explore trends of pieces that have known dates. After reading the cleaned csv files, we created separate data framesâone containing artworks with known dates, and another containing artworks without dates. This allows us to exclusively work with the art pieces with known dates, and apply those trends to the artworks with unknown dates. A great way to approximate the dates of the mysterious artworks would be to examine the trends for artworks of similar mediums. Throughout time, there have been trends for different mediums of art. For instance, painting was an extremely popular medium during the renaissance, and digital art is a growing trend in the modern age. Analyzing these trends would provide us with a span of time where we could assume an artwork with a missing date should have been created.

However, realizing that there are a vast variety of mediums noted in the data frame, we decided to focus our research on the top ten most common mediums. Using a list of the top ten most common mediums, we separated all the artworks of those mediums from the others.

Code 
#lists of top 10 mediums for artists with missing dates
moma_unknown_med = moma_unknown['Medium'].value_counts()[0:10].index.tolist()
tate_unknown_med = tate_unknown['medium'].value_counts()[0:10].index.tolist()

#dataframes with all works under the listed mediums
moma_med = moma_works_cleaned[moma_works_cleaned['Medium'].isin(moma_unknown_med)]
tate_med = tate_works_cleaned[tate_works_cleaned['medium'].isin(tate_unknown_med)]

After clearing the outliers from the data, we created graphs that depicted the distribution of mediums throughout time. These distributions confirm that mediums grew and declined in popularity throughout time. Each medium had a range of years where it faced its peak in popularity. Finally, to answer our question, we calculated a confidence interval that allows us to be 95% confident that an artwork of a given medium was created between the ranges of the resulting interval. For instance, at MoMA, we are 95% confident that a letterpress artwork was created between 1934 and 1935.

Code 
#finding outliers for moma
moma_no_outliers = moma_med[0:0]
for i in moma_unknown_med:
    temp = moma_med.loc[moma_med['Medium'] == i]
    q1, q3= np.percentile(temp.Date,[25,75])
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower_bound = q1 - 1.5*iqr
    upper_bound = q3 + 1.5*iqr

    no_outliers = temp[((temp.Date>=lower_bound) & (temp.Date<=upper_bound))]
    moma_no_outliers = pd.concat([moma_no_outliers, no_outliers])
    
#finding outliers for tate
tate_no_outliers = tate_med[0:0]
for i in tate_unknown_med:
    temp = tate_med.loc[tate_med['medium'] == i]
    q1, q3= np.percentile(temp.year,[25,75])
    iqr = q3 - q1
    lower_bound = q1 - 1.5*iqr
    upper_bound = q3 + 1.5*iqr

    no_outliers = temp[((temp.year>=lower_bound) & (temp.year<=upper_bound))]
    tate_no_outliers = pd.concat([tate_no_outliers, no_outliers])

#function for calculating confidence interval
def standard_dev(df, medium, date):
    mean = df[date].mean()
    sd = df[date].std()
    n = len(df)
    Zstar = 1.96
    se = sd/np.sqrt(n)
    lower = round(mean - Zstar * se)
    upper = round(mean + Zstar * se)
    print(f'{medium}: ({lower}, {upper})')

By Lila Weiner

As previously mentioned, the first step in exploring artwork age was to prepare the columns which signified creation date. To account for common cases of creation dates, we subsetted these inputs using a series of filtering processes. After addressing these cases, we converted the year column to numeric in order to analyze the variable. To create a new âartwork ageâ column, we subtracted the creation date from 2022. We also added a column to each dataset, which specified the museum. This column proved to be useful after we concatenated the artwork ages of all of the museums.

Code

Once we added the new columns, we computed the summary statistics of artwork age. Initially, we subsetted the three datasets for the new âmuseum nameâ and âartwork ageâ columns, and then vertically concatenated these subsetted datasets. From here, we grouped the concatenated dataset by âmuseum nameâ, and computed the mean, median, and standard deviation of artwork age using .agg(). The standard deviation of the Block museum is higher than the other two museums, which indicates the larger variation of the museumâs collection. The Block museumâs variation is notable, as it proves that a small scale museum has a relative ability to collect old and new artworks alike.

The artwork age distribution of Tateâs collection is significantly older than the Moma and Block museums. While the Tate distribution is centered around 150 years, most of the Moma and Block artworks are under 100 years old. Generally, the distribution trends align with the mean age of the three museums, as the mean age for Tate is approximately 72 years older than the Block, and 90 years older than the Moma. Tateâs older artwork collection could be attributed to the museum age. The Tate Museum was founded in 1897, and is the oldest of the three museums. Tate museum is also located in England, and is in closer geographic proximity to artworks that were produced in Eastern centered art movements. Also, the continued act of preserving older artworks is costly: the physical elements of an aged artwork require meticulous upkeep, temperature regulation and protection. Hence, the Tate museum is opportunely situated in regard to location and time, and might also have more resources to collect older artworks. Following the stacked histogram of artwork age, we decided to compare artwork age and acquisition year. The acquisition date column is only present in the Moma and Tate datasets, so the Block data was not used in this regard. For the two datasets, we made a new column âacquisition ageâ that is the acquisition year subtracted by the creation year. Acquisition date was initially represented by a year-month-day string in both dataframes, so we subsetted for the four digit year in order to complete the subtraction. Finally, we plotted the âacquisition ageâ using displot() to visualize the distribution.

By Gabrielle Bliss

The demographic analysis of artists represented in the MoMA, Tate, and Block museums utilized the museum artist databases the most, and aims to depict the representation of artists by nationality and gender in order to inform future acquisitions. As aforementioned in the background of our project, a general consensus among museums today is that their collections should avoid overlooking historically marginalized groups, and by performing an analysis of nationality and gender of represented artists in these three museums, acquisitionists and other stakeholders will be informed on how to better make ethical acquisitions.

Using the clean data in the gender columns of the Tate and MoMA datasets, I was able to create a visualization of gender distribution for both of these museums using a stacked barplot. This stacked barplot visualized the distribution between âMaleâ and âFemaleâ genders for both museums, while also displaying the proportion of artists that identify as âNon-Binaryâ in the MoMAâs collection. In order to achieve this particular visualization, the crosstab() function had to be used on both of the gender columns for both museums, with a normalizing argument in order to visualize proportions. A distribution visualization with regards to proportion of genders in represented artists was ideal since the sample size of genders for artists in both museums differed.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

def pct_remove(limit):
    """Remove percent on small slices."""
    def inner_pct(pct):
        return ('%.0f%%' % pct) if pct > limit else ''
    return inner_pct

#defining Seaborn color palette to use
colors = sns.color_palette('pastel')[0:len(moma_artists.Nationality.value_counts())]

7 Conclusions

  1. After analyzing the trends for dated artworks, we were able to conclude on a confidence interval that allows museums to be 95% confident about the date an undated artwork was created. Based on these confidence intervals, we can conclude on the historical context behind the artwork, which ultimately provides deeper insight into the artworkâs meaning and significance.

  2. In terms of mediums, both museums heavily featured mediums related to photography which can be justified by the fact that both Museums have an emphasis on modern works, especially MoMA. When looking at mediums in relation to time however, we saw that all of the top 5 mediums had a âpeakâ in terms of artworks done with that medium, suggesting that mediums are only popular for a short period of time. Lastly, when looking at dimensions both museums seemed to suggest that artworks have been growing in size since the 1800s, with the Tate museum having older works that vary a lot in size.

  3. Generally, the Tate museum has an older collection of artworks than the Moma and Block museums. This may be due to the geographic location, size, and status of the Tate museum. Additionally, the Tate and Moma typically acquire artworks a few years after the artwork was created, according to the two histograms.

  4. Distribution of gender in both major museums analyzed (Tate and MoMA) is heavily dominated by male-identifying artists; around 80% of artists represented in artwork collections are male. The MoMA had slightly better diversity in terms of representing a slightly higher proportion of female artists and including non-binary artists in their collection. The distributions of nationality highlight the dominance of European and American artists represented in these museums. We can possibly attribute this to the fact that the museum collections also consist of artwork âgiftsâ from locals and alumni rather than specific acquisitions by the museum. In future analyses, data regarding these artists and demographics could be weighted by the amount of art pieces they have provided to the museumsâ collections.

8 Recommendations to stakeholders

In our first analysis, our stakeholders are presented with a 95% confidence interval that estimates when an artwork was created. The confidence intervals present art curators the chance to realize further trends of artworks throughout time. With this information, curators can better understand the artwork and its role in the historical context of when it was created, and refer to these estimated intervals when looking for an artwork from a specific time period to acquire. Also, art curators can present visitors with more accurate information about the artwork dates through our confidence intervals, which presents a deeper comprehension of trends of acquired artworks.

The second analysis depicts the most pervasive mediums featured in the museums which to stakeholders, specifically museum curators, signals that there needs to be more diversity in terms of the mediums of the work. A potential solution to this would be to introduce artworks with mediums that originated from underrepresented countries as opposed to popular mediums that feature mainly European artists. Further, looking at the dimensions, there seems to be an upward trend in the size of artworks since the 1800s. For art researchers there is an interesting trend in terms of art dimensions in relation to time.

While all three museums contain both old and new artworks, there are measures that can be taken in order to ensure that smaller scale museums can present historical works of art to their audiences. We suggest that larger museums, such as the Tate museum, loan older artworks to small scale museums for temporary exhibitions. Temporary exhibitions succeed in spreading artwork of differing ages to new audiences, and promoting the museum that is lending the art. There are financial costs of temporary exhibitions, since they require considerable effort to transport artworks carefully. However, two museums in close proximity could organize a temporary exhibition without shipping artworks across states/countries. For instance, the Art Institute of Chicago and the Block Museum might consider collaborating in order to bring works from the Art Institute to Northwesternâs campus. There are also organizations in place to guide the creation of temporary exhibitions, such as the Touring Exhibitions Group, based in the United Kingdom.

The analysis of artist demographics primarily provides the most pertinent, specific recommendations to museum acquisition teams and collectors, as opposed to the other stakeholders that our project could be applicable to. When making acquisitions, in order to further diversify the artists represented in the various museumsâ collections, acquisition teams can look to these distributions to inform where they are lacking in terms of representation. For example, all analyzed museums could increase their representation of artists with Asian nationalities. The Tate and MoMA should focus acquisitions on works done by artists that are female-identifying or of another gender than male when looking to diversify their collections in terms of these variables.
